ARTICLE.TITLE: Hundreds of people come out to safely commemorate VJ Day in Cleethorpes
ARTICLE.TEXT:
Sign up to FREE email alerts from GrimsbyLive - Daily Subscribe Thank you for subscribing See our privacy notice Invalid Email

Crowds of people gathered in Cleethorpes this morning to pay their respect to Victory over Japan Day.

More than 100 people visited the WWII Remembrance Gate in Cleethorpes to listen to Armed Forces representatives and pay their respects to both veterans and those who lost their lives in the conflict.

There was a short parade to the Remembrance Gate, which was led by bagpiper Danny Flemming, with speeches from several people including Deputy Lieutenant for Lincolnshire, Alex Baxter, and a two-minute silence to mark the occasion.

Despite the large crowds, social distancing was in place at all times while people paid respects for those who lost their lives.

This is the first time that the country has been able to pay their respects to the 75th Anniversary of the end of World War II, with the coronavirus stopping VE Day celebrations from going ahead in their traditional sense.

(Image: Jon Corken/Grimsby Live)

Deputy Lieutenant Alex Baxter, who also the Armed Forces Champion for North East Lincolnshire, said: "It's nice to have people out here to pay their respects today.

"Because it's a commemoration, it was well planned and everyone was aware of social distancing, so everyone stayed safe.

"Even the veterans who came down here today to support the ceremony were wearing masks, it's good to see that we can pay our respects while being safe.

"But we will never forget those who lost their lives in this conflict, and the sacrifices they made for our nation.

"I think we can take a lot from the people who lost their lives and apply it to today. Going through the pandemic is almost diving into the unknown, with this being the first thing we have experienced since the Spanish Flu 100 years ago.

(Image: Jon Corken/Grimsby Live)

"Like the military, the people of the NHS always stand up and fight through for our country. I think that young people of this nation will get through this stronger than ever."

Gemma Leaning, Community Fundraiser for Lincolnshire with the Royal British Legion, said: "It was lovely to be involved today and help out. It's a personal one for me too, because my grandad was a Prisoner of War in Japan, so it was for me to be here.

"We didn't advertise it as much because we didn't want to bring in the crowds, so we just invited some veterans to take part.

"But people in the area are very passionate about the Armed Forces and seemed to find out, either way, and have come down to show their support.

"It's been nice today, it isn't as well publicised as VE Day, but it was the end of the war and there was a lot of suffering there, so it's important we pay our respects and commemorate them today."

(Image: Jon Corken/Grimsby Live)

Great Grimsby MP, Lia Nici, and Cleethorpes MP, Martin Vickers were also at the ceremony to show their support and pay their respects.

Lia Nici said: "It's an honour to be able to come here and meet with veterans and commemorate the terrible campaign that our sailors and soldiers had endured.

"The Allies were a largely diverse army, which I think can be looked at in this day and age as something to take on board for ourselves. Everyone working together for a better future.

"We should be very blessed to live in a country like the UK, and I am proud to be here to represent Great Grimsby today."

Martin Vickers added: "It is very important to mark these occasions and pay our respect. The soldiers of World War II made a large sacrifice for our country and it is important to keep paying tribute to them as we have today.

"It is a shame that we can't put on a full ceremony, but it is the best thing to do to keep people safe while also being able to pay our respects."

Elsewhere in North East Lincolnshire, there was a small ceremony at New Waltham, with local veterans and the Royal British Legion coming out to pay their respects at the memorial there.
